Good Evening Lakers,

The board of education has approved the reopening framework for next school year as well as a revised school calendar. Parents should visit the district website at www.walnuttsd.org and click the tab at the top titled 2020-2021 reopening. On this page, you will find the reopening plan, updated school calendar with August 25 as the student's first day, detailed information for the two options you can select for next year, Laker Virtual Academy Application, Facial Covering Requirement, transportation and frequently asked questions. Parents that wish to enroll their child in the Laker Virtual Academy must complete the online application by August 5. Thank you for your patience and we will be announcing the model the district will reopen for students very soon.

Have a great evening,

Will Kirby
Superintendent Designee

Federal Dislocated Worker Grant:

Ohio received an $8.5 million federal Employment Recovery National Dislocated Worker Grant to help reemploy Ohioans who lost their jobs as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic and to help employers rebuild their workforces. The agency will distribute the funding to Ohio's local workforce areas and work in partnership with them to provide outreach to employers and services to individuals who were laid off permanently or temporarily as a result of the pandemic. Allowable services will include paid work experience, on-the-job training, customized training, skills upgrading and supportive services, in addition to personal protective equipment and other supplies… More

Class of 2020 and Families,

The graduation ceremony for today, Sunday June 28, will take place at 7:30 p.m. tonight in the stadium. Graduates are reminded to arrive at 6 p.m. and park in the student parking lot so guests can park next to the stadium. Guests can begin entering the stadium at 6:30 p.m. Please remember to bring your face masks and ensure you maintain at least 6 feet of social distance between family groups. We strongly encourage all graduates and guests to bring bottled water with them. We will see you at 7:30 to honor our Class of 2020.

--

Will Kirby
Curriculum Coordinator
Walnut Township Local Schools

Dear Class of 2020,

Due to a changeover of the student information system, the OneCall system was updated automatically on Friday and removed the class of 2020 from the 12th grade group in the system. This is entirely my fault in not verifying that an update to the system did not occur. I have now manually re-created the Class of 2020 group in the OneCall system in preparation for tomorrow’s ceremony. In the event you did not get a call, we will post all information on the district website, Laker Pride Page, Parent Page and send out notification via email to seniors and via senior class president. Once again, I take full responsibility for the absence of a OneCall today.

Sincerely,

Will Kirby

SUPERINTENDENT FAREWELL:

Dear Students, Staff and Community,

It is with a heavy heart that I am writing my final superintendent message to you. I came to the Walnut Township Local School District nine years ago as your athletic director/dean of students/math teacher. Over those nine years I have developed a special place in my heart for your schools and community.

With my office being located directly beside the kindergarten rooms, I am able to meet our students right at the beginning of their school career. That is a special benefit that very few superintendents experience. The smallness of our district is another benefit that allows me to get to know ALL of our students and staff.

My…

OASSA Members:
Please see the following info regarding the the Pandemic-EBT (P-EBT) program:

As you may have already seen, the Pandemic-EBT (P-EBT) program – which provides federal funding for families with children to purchase food during the pandemic – has launched in the State of Ohio.

Children’s Defense Fund-Ohio, along with a working group of anti-hunger and children’s advocates and in partnership with the Ohio Department of Job and Family Services and the Ohio Department of Education, is working to raise awareness about the program to families.

Robocall Example: https://mcusercontent.com/7169653d29a7bd92bd770354b/files/73b5f361-d2b8-4001-848d-7ba1fce3e3d3/Robocall_Script.pdf

Informational PDF: https://mcusercontent.com/7169653d29a7bd92bd770354b/files/45691bb2-c167-4db8-a9d5-04883e7c5fdf/information_graphic_and_letter.pdf

See FAQs here: http://ohiopebt.org/.

Thermometers:

Energy Optimizers, USA has "no touch" thermometers available for sale ($85). Contact Mike Richards at 419-303-6122 if you need to order!
Website: https://energyoptusa.com/

Working hard with passion and vigor for the things you grow to love and respect. Accomplishments that define who you are and an end that takes you down a road of gratitude.

WELCOME TO THE MHS 2020 SENIOR HIGHLIGHT!

STEPHEN ALEXANDER WARNER

I'm Stephen Warner, a senior at Millersport High School planning to pursue Music Education at Capital University. I have been involved in everything music in the High School, along with various sports and clubs, such as Track and Field as a thrower, Soccer Captain my Junior year as goalkeeper, and as Treasurer in the Spanish Club. I serve on the Student Council and in the High School's Chapter on the National Honors Society. My favorite memory was our last band competition on our 3 hour journey to Ironton. It was all fun and games, even if we didn't make state, but still made history in our records as a band. I look forward to my future career and wish my fellow classmates the best of luck in their future endeavors.

ATTENTION MILLERSPORT FAMILIES:

WHAT: Raising Cane’s Ohio and the OHSAA partner to provide funding for student-athletes across Ohio

WHERE: Your closest Raising Cane’s location (All Raising Cane’s locations in Ohio)

WHEN: Thursday, April 30, 2020. 4pm – Close.

In a statewide effort to help serve schools, Raising Cane’s Ohio has stepped up and partnered with the Ohio High School Athletic Association. This support comes at a vital time and will help provide funding for student-athlete scholarship programs and postseason tournaments. With 36 locations across Ohio, Cane’s is known for its chicken finger meals, customer satisfaction and supporting the communities they serve.

On Thursday, April 30, please encourage your community to choose Raising Cane’s for dinner. A portion of all sales from 4 p.m. to close will go towards helping the OHSAA serve its members across the state. By serving Cane’s, you’ll be serving Ohio schools. Join us by posting a photo of your combo with the hashtag #CANESxOHSAA to show your support for interscholastic athletics throughout our state.

Celebrate your appreciation:

April and May are full of national appreciation days: teachers, principal, nurse, school lunch heroes, secretaries, bus drivers, and more. Our elementary student council would typically show appreciation in the form of cards, posters, and gifts. With that not possible at the moment, we would love to put together a video to show all of these wonderful people how much they are appreciated. If you and/or your child would like to show your appreciation with a message, picture, or video, please send your submission to kmckibben@walnuttsd.org by May 1st. Messages can be to individual people or to a group of people. You can also submit as many messages as you'd like!

post_text:
Have you ever wondered where the Anchor in front of the HS/JH came from? How it got here and who was responsible for finding it?

A few pieces of the History of the Anchor are mapped out in the letters below. In 1972, Millersport Superintendent Ed Brookover forwarded a letter to Congressional Representative Clarence E. Miller requesting assistance with obtaining a surplus anchor(s). These three pieces of correspondence give us a little insight into the events that followed. Although further details were not available, the Anchor is holding steadfast and represents the strength and resilience of the Millersport Lakers! Stay strong and Stay PROUD!

WELCOME TO THE MHS 2020 SENIOR HIGHLIGHT!

HAILEY AUTUMN BLANCHARD

I am Hailey Blanchard and I am a senior at Millersport High School. After I graduate, I plan to attend Ohio University and double major in Spanish and Spanish Education. Coming up with a favorite memory of my high school experience is nearly impossible. I have found something special in every single day. However, with that being said, a few of my favorite memories include Christmas caroling through the halls with Mr. Keener, doing a scavenger hunt through the school in A.P. Language, and the Edgar René Spanish concert. I would like to thank all of the teachers and staff at Millersport for giving me such an amazing experience and all of my fellow seniors for all of the shared laughter over the years.

As you are aware, the Coronavirus issues going on around the globe. Millersport Schools is taking a pro-active approach to prepare for the possibility of schools being closed for an extended period by authority of the State of Ohio or federal entity.

post_text: 8th Grade field trip to the State House on Friday. A great experience! The eighth grade class had the opportunity to take a trip to the Ohio Statehouse due to the generosity of an Ohio Statehouse Transportation Grant. Students had the opportunity to tour the Ohio Statehouse and learn many historical and current facts about our wonderful state's government. Some of the students' favorite parts of the tour were seeing the beautifully embellished domed ceiling of the rotunda, viewing the "Battle of Lake Erie" painting (worth over two-million dollars), and learning about the imported marble that decorates the interior of the Statehouse. It was also interesting to learn about the extensive restoration project that has taken seven years to complete. It was an enriching educational trip as students learned about Ohio's government and how it works to serve all of our eighty-eighth counties.

post_text: Have you used an augmented reality sandbox? Our 4th graders had an amazing experience this week thanks to the Fairfield Soil and Water Conservation District! Students explored topographic maps and landforms using an augmented reality sandbox. This sandbox allows students to create landforms using kinetic sand and projects a topographic map in real time with contour lines and color gradients to represent elevation changes. Their creations were displayed for other students to view on our Smartboard. Students could also "make it rain" using their hands to see the effect of water on their landform creations and Earth's surface. Thank you Tommy and Carrie from FSWCD!
